:: title ::

# MCP Apps - What Changes

:: left ::

**Before MCP Apps**, your MCP server returns text:

<div class="p-3 rounded bg-gray-800 font-mono text-xs mt-2 mb-4">
<span class="text-gray-400">$</span> show-catalog<br/>
<span class="text-gray-500">5 services found: user-service<br/>(healthy), payment-api (healthy),<br/>notification-svc (degraded),<br/>api-gateway (healthy), auth-service<br/>(healthy)</span>
</div>

The developer reads a wall of text, copies a service name, types another command, repeats. The MCP server is powerful but **invisible**.

:: right ::

**With MCP Apps**, the same tool renders a real UI:

<div class="p-3 rounded border-1 border-solid border-teal-400 bg-gray-800 mt-2 mb-4">
  <div class="text-teal-300 text-xs mb-2 font-semibold">Platform Service Catalog</div>
  <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-1">
    <div class="bg-gray-700 rounded p-1.5 text-xs">
      <div class="font-semibold text-gray-200">user-service</div>
      <div class="text-green-400 text-[10px]">● healthy</div>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-gray-700 rounded p-1.5 text-xs">
      <div class="font-semibold text-gray-200">payment-api</div>
      <div class="text-green-400 text-[10px]">● healthy</div>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-gray-700 rounded p-1.5 text-xs">
      <div class="font-semibold text-gray-200">notification-svc</div>
      <div class="text-amber-400 text-[10px]">● degraded</div>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-gray-700 rounded p-1.5 text-xs">
      <div class="font-semibold text-gray-200">api-gateway</div>
      <div class="text-green-400 text-[10px]">● healthy</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mt-2">
    <span class="px-2 py-0.5 bg-indigo-500 text-white text-[10px] rounded">Deploy</span>
    <span class="px-2 py-0.5 bg-gray-600 text-gray-300 text-[10px] rounded ml-1">Details</span>
  </div>
</div>

Click. Browse. Deploy. **Inside the conversation.** The same MCP server, the same data - but now with a face.

<!--
This is the before and after of MCP Apps. Same server, same data. Left: a text dump the developer has to parse mentally. Right: an interactive card they can click, browse, and deploy from - without leaving the conversation. The UI runs in a sandboxed iframe, zero token cost, and it works in Claude, VS Code, Goose, and ChatGPT today.
-->

---
layout: top-title
color: navy
align: l
---

:: title ::

# How MCP Apps Work

:: content ::

<div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-6">
<div>

**The flow:**

<div class="ns-c-tight text-sm">

1. Developer asks: _"Show me the service catalog"_
2. LLM calls your MCP tool: `show-catalog`
3. Tool returns **data** + pointer to **UI resource**
4. Host fetches bundled HTML from `ui://catalog/app.html`
5. Renders interactive UI in a **sandboxed iframe**
6. Developer clicks "Deploy" inside the UI
7. UI calls **app-only tool** back to server
8. Deployment runs, UI updates inline

</div>

</div>
<div>

**Key concepts:**

<Admonition title="Two-part registration" color="emerald-light">
**Tool** returns data + `_meta.ui.resourceUri`
**Resource** serves the bundled HTML
</Admonition>

<Admonition title="App-only tools" color="blue-light">
Tools the **UI can call** but the **LLM cannot see**. User stays in control of actions like deploy.
</Admonition>

<Admonition title="Zero token cost" color="green-light">
UI is served as a resource, not generated as tokens.
</Admonition>

</div>
</div>

<!--
Two-part registration: tool and resource, linked by a URI. The tool returns data plus a pointer to the UI. The host fetches the HTML, renders it sandboxed. The UI can call app-only tools - tools the model can't see, only the user can trigger. All through secure postMessage. Zero token cost.
-->

---
layout: top-title
color: navy
align: l
---

:: title ::

# Server Side: Your Catalog as an MCP App

:: content ::

```ts {all|3-5|7-12|all} twoslash
// @noErrors
import { registerAppTool, registerAppResource } from "@modelcontextprotocol/ext-apps/server";

// Register a tool that returns data + points to a UI
registerAppTool(server, "show-catalog", {
  title: "Platform Service Catalog",
  description: "Shows all registered platform services",
  _meta: { ui: { resourceUri: "ui://catalog/app.html" } },
}, async () => ({
  content: [{ type: "text", text: "5 services found" }],     // text fallback
  structuredContent: { view: "catalog", services: [/*...*/] }, // data for UI
}));

// Register the HTML resource the tool references
registerAppResource(server, "catalog-ui", "ui://catalog/app.html", {}, async () => ({
  contents: [{ uri: "ui://catalog/app.html", text: html }],
}));
```

<!--
That's it. Two registrations linked by a URI. The tool returns structured data for the UI plus a text fallback for hosts that don't support MCP Apps. The resource serves the bundled HTML. Under 200 lines for the whole server.
-->

---
layout: top-title
color: navy
align: l
---

:: title ::

# Client Side: Inside the Conversation

:: content ::

```ts {all|1-5|7-9|11-15|17-20|all} twoslash
// @noErrors
import { App } from "@modelcontextprotocol/ext-apps";

const app = new App({ name: "Service Catalog", version: "1.0.0" });
await app.connect();

// Receive tool results with structured data
app.ontoolresult = (result) => {
  renderUI(result.structuredContent);
};

// Call tools back to the server from the UI
document.getElementById("deploy-btn").addEventListener("click", async () => {
  const result = await app.callServerTool({
    name: "deploy-service",
    arguments: { serviceId: "user-service", environment: "staging" },
  });
});

// Adapt to host theme
app.onhostcontextchanged = (ctx) => {
  document.documentElement.style.colorScheme = ctx.themeMode;
};
```

<!--
Sandboxed iframe. Standard web APIs - addEventListener, DOM manipulation. Receives tool results, renders UI, calls tools back to the server. If you can build a web app, you can build this.
-->

