---

:: title ::

# OpenUI by Thesys

:: left ::

**The problem:** Every MCP App needs hand-built HTML. That doesn't scale to hundreds of tools.

**The idea:** Let the AI generate UI, but constrain it to a **component catalog** defined by your platform team.

<div class="ns-c-tight mt-2">

- Platform team defines components with **Zod schemas**
- AI generates compact component references, not HTML
- Runtime renders real React components
- **~40 tokens** per component vs ~2,000 for raw HTML

</div>

:: right ::

```tsx
// Platform team defines the catalog
const ServiceCard = defineComponent({
  name: "ServiceCard",
  props: z.object({
    name: z.string(),
    health: z.enum(["healthy", "degraded"]),
    team: z.string(),
  }),
  component: ({ props }) => (
    <Card status={props.health}>
      <h3>{props.name}</h3>
      <span>{props.team}</span>
    </Card>
  ),
});

// AI output: ~40 tokens
<ServiceCard
  name="Payment API"
  health="healthy"
  team="Commerce" />
```

<div class="text-xs opacity-50 mt-2">@openuidev/react-lang - published 2026</div>

<!--
OpenUI solves the scaling problem. With MCP Apps you build a custom HTML app per tool. With OpenUI, your platform team defines a component catalog with Zod schemas - what components exist, what props they accept. The AI generates compact references - 40 tokens instead of 2,000. The runtime renders real React components. It's golden paths for UI - the same concept platform teams already apply to infrastructure.
-->

---
layout: top-title-two-cols
color: navy
align: l-lt-lt
---

:: title ::

# json-render by Vercel Labs

:: left ::

**The problem:** Your platform UI needs to render in the IDE, in a mobile app, in email notifications, and in PDF reports. MCP Apps only work in MCP hosts.

**The idea:** One JSON schema, rendered on **any platform**.

<div class="ns-c-tight mt-2">

- Define component catalog with Zod schemas
- AI generates a JSON spec describing the UI
- **Streaming-first** - renders as tokens arrive
- Renderers for React, React Native, email, PDF, terminal
- `@json-render/mcp` package for MCP integration

</div>

:: right ::

```ts
// Define catalog
const catalog = defineCatalog(schema, {
  components: {
    ServiceStatus: {
      props: z.object({
        name: z.string(),
        status: z.enum(["running", "stopped"]),
        replicas: z.number(),
      }),
    },
  },
});

// AI generates JSON spec
const spec = {
  root: "s1",
  elements: {
    s1: {
      type: "ServiceStatus",
      props: {
        name: "API Gateway",
        status: "running",
        replicas: 4,
      },
    },
  },
};
// Renders on ANY platform
```

<div class="text-xs opacity-50 mt-2">@json-render/core + @json-render/react - v0.17, published 2026</div>

<!--
json-render tackles a different problem. Your platform isn't just an IDE tool - you need the same service status card in mobile push notifications, in email digests, in PDF compliance reports, and in AI conversations. json-render lets you define one JSON schema that renders on any platform. Streaming-first means the UI builds as tokens arrive from the AI.
-->

---
layout: top-title-two-cols
color: navy
align: l-lt-lt
---

:: title ::

# AG-UI by CopilotKit

:: left ::

**The problem:** You're building your own AI-powered platform frontend, not using Claude Desktop or ChatGPT. You need a protocol for agent-to-UI communication.

**The idea:** A **standardized event protocol** between AI agent backends and your React frontend.

<div class="ns-c-tight mt-2">

- 16 event types: lifecycle, text, tools, state
- Bidirectional state sync via JSON Patch
- Framework-agnostic backend (LangGraph, CrewAI, etc.)
- **2M+ weekly downloads**
- 30K GitHub stars on CopilotKit

</div>

:: right ::

```tsx
// Your React frontend
useCopilotAction({
  name: "showDeployStatus",
  description: "Show deployment status",
  parameters: [
    { name: "serviceId", type: "string" },
    { name: "env", type: "string" },
  ],
  // AI triggers this, React renders it
  render: ({ status, args }) => (
    <DeployStatusCard
      serviceId={args.serviceId}
      env={args.env}
      loading={status === "executing"}
    />
  ),
});

// AG-UI events flow over the wire:
// RUN_STARTED → TOOL_CALL_START →
// STATE_DELTA → TOOL_CALL_END
```

<div class="text-xs opacity-50 mt-2">@copilotkit/react-core v1.55 + @ag-ui/client v0.0.52</div>

<!--
AG-UI is for when you're building your own platform frontend. Maybe you're building a custom engineering dashboard, not relying on Claude Desktop. AG-UI standardizes how agent backends talk to your React frontend - 16 event types, bidirectional state sync, works with any agent framework. CopilotKit has 30K GitHub stars and 2M weekly downloads. This is production-grade.
-->

---
layout: top-title
color: navy
align: l
---

:: title ::

# MCP Apps vs Generative UI - When to Use What

:: content ::

| | **MCP Apps** | **OpenUI** | **json-render** | **AG-UI** |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Best for** | Rich interactive apps | High-volume chat UIs | Multi-platform delivery | Custom platform frontends |
| **UI richness** | Full HTML/JS/CSS | Component catalog | JSON schema | React components |
| **Token cost** | Zero (bundled) | Low (~40/card) | Medium | N/A (transport) |
| **Who builds UI?** | You (HTML) | AI (constrained) | AI (constrained) | You (React) |
| **Host required** | Claude, ChatGPT, VS Code | Any with OpenUI runtime | Any renderer | Your own app |
| **Platform use case** | Service catalog, deploy flows | Status pages, alerts | Reports, notifications | Engineering dashboard |

<v-click>

<Admonition title="They're not competing" color="purple-light">
MCP Apps for deep interactions. OpenUI for scale. json-render for reach. AG-UI for custom hosts. A real platform team uses **multiple approaches** for different workflows.
</Admonition>

</v-click>

<!--
This is not a "pick one" decision. MCP Apps when you need full control - service catalogs, deploy workflows, complex forms. OpenUI when you have hundreds of tools and can't hand-build UI for each. json-render when you need the same UI across mobile, email, and web. AG-UI when you're building your own platform frontend. These are complementary layers.
-->

---
layout: top-title
color: navy
align: l
---

:: title ::

# What To Do Monday Morning

:: content ::

<div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-3">

<Admonition title="1. Audit your portal" color="indigo-light">
Which workflows have the lowest adoption? Those are your MCP candidates.
</Admonition>

<Admonition title="2. Build one MCP server" color="indigo-light">
Start with service catalog or deploy. `registerAppTool` + `registerAppResource`. Under 200 lines.
</Admonition>

<Admonition title="3. Measure against your portal" color="indigo-light">
Track tool calls, UI renders, time-to-action. Compare adoption rates.
</Admonition>

<Admonition title="4. Plan for the stack" color="purple-light">
MCP Apps for deep flows. Consider OpenUI or json-render as your tool count grows. Evaluate AG-UI if you're building a custom frontend.
</Admonition>

</div>

<!--
Four things for Monday. Audit your lowest-adoption portal workflows. Build one MCP server - under 200 lines. Measure. And plan for the broader stack as your tool count grows. Your portal is your context layer. MCP is how agents access it.
-->

